11	 News Sports Weather Traffic Lifestyles Entertainment Classifieds WBRZ-TV The Advocate Obituaries Advertisements Customer Service GENERAL SERVICES Contact Us FAQs Advocate history WBRZ history Site Map SUBSCRIBER SERVICES Subscribe Now! Delivery Questions Vacation Stop/Start NEWS SERVICES Letter to editor Engagement Weddings Obituaries WBRZ Scripts READER / VIEWER SERVICES Email Newsletters Archives Back Issues Education (NIE) Sports Posters Photo/Page Reprints Video Copies ADVERTISING SERVICES Place a classified ad Advocate Advertising Questions WBRZ Advertising Questions Advertisements   2theadvocate > News > Blanco, senators pleased with President Bush meeting 09/03/05 Blanco, senators pleased with President Bush meeting By REBECCA BREEDEN rbreeden@theadvocate.com 2theadvocate.com staff writer Gov. Kathleen Blanco spent the day with President Bush in what she called a productive day. Blanco asked Bush to send home Louisiana National Guard's 256th combat brigade team from Iraq to help with hurricane aftermath. Some soldiers will have no houses or jobs when they return home. "I'm hearing that a lot of those soldiers are extremely upset about what's happening here and are looking forward to working close to home," Blanco said Friday night. "Our people would rather work closer to home." Bush didn't respond to that request. However, faith has been renewed for Louisiana citizens, Blanco said, and New Orleans Mayor Ray Nagin has a "renewed sense of hope" after being under a tremendous amount of stress. Project Hope is the new name given to rebuilding southeast Louisiana. Advertisements "It was just a beautiful thing, and I thought about what it symbolized ? the first ray of real hope for the people who have lost so much," Blanco said. "It means the beginning of the end of the nightmare. There are better days to come." A 501C3 non-profit was created today to better coordinate donations. People can send donations to the Louisiana Disaster Recovery Foundation, P.O. Box 94095, Baton Rouge, LA 70804-9095. The donations will go toward refugees' housing, education, healthcare, and jobs. Visit http://www.louisiana.gov for details. Blanco said Bush spent Friday on the ground watching workers work on the levee and the military's response to hurricane aftermath. Blanco asked for at least 40,000 troops throughout Louisiana. More than 2,000 soldiers will arrive by midnight, making the grand total 7,000. "We have to restore order so that we can begin the process of rebuilding," Blanco said. "People have to be able to walk safely. We cannot have people threatening our citizens and making their lives unsafe." Trailers of water, ice, food, or commercial buses, base camps, staging areas, amphibious personnel carriers, airlift, urban search teams, generators, fuel and communication systems were also on Blanco's wish list. The casualties are still unknown, but the governor expects thousands. The Superdome is practically empty, but the New Orleans Convention Center is still largely occupied. Citizens there will be evacuated Saturday morning. Sen. David Vitter called FEMA's response to the hurricane aftermath an "abject failure." He said he was frustrated that FEMA didn't have a more reasonable plan to something "utterly predictable." He suggested putting Lt. Gen. Russell Honore, a Louisiana native, in charge. Vitter and Sen. Mary Landrieu also spent the day with Bush and Blanco flying over neighborhoods, cities and parishes affected by Katrina. Landrieu asked Bush to appoint a cabinet-level person to immediately coordinate money to rebuild New Orleans and surrounding parishes. She said FEMA's focus hasn't worked this week, but that Bush could make bold decisions to make things happen. "America should never allow this to happen again," Landrieu said. "Forgive us if you think we've made mistakes," she said, adding that lack of investment, communication, organization and the ability to grasp the situation have complicated everything. She said she was confident that after today Bush understood the magnitude of crisis, and that he should make bold decisions. Bush made no promises. "I'm hopeful that today's a turning point," Vitter said. "I learned the last four days not to believe anything until I see it." Printer Friendly Version Send this story to a friend Advertisements FEATURES
