's this week. Contractions while packing Katherine, on maternity leave from an insurance company, and Mark Bacchus, a telecommunications worker, were deciding where to go as the hurricane turned toward New Orleans. "My contractions started while I was packing," Bacchus said. Bacchus checked with her doctor, Thomas Ryan, who told her Memorial Medical was being evacuated. "Dr. Ryan said meet him at his house on Prytania," Bacchus said. "He was really sweet. No doctor's going to go to that much trouble, but he delivered my three other children." The couple's third son, Marcell, was with his grandmother. The Bacchuses don't know where Marcell is, but they assume he and his grandmother got out of the city with friends. On the way to Prytania Street, the couple decided to swing by Katherine Bacchus' dad's house on South Gayoso near Earhart Boulevard. "The sky looked funny," she said, "but there was no rain." Riding out the storm Bacchus' father was out of town, so she and her husband began getting the house ready for the storm. With nightfall, they decided to bunk down on the second floor of the house. "Then, windows started breaking and the house started shaking," Mark Bacchus said. "We were trying to plug holes and save as much as we could." His wife's contractions got harder. "It's pitch black, and the wind's blowing like heck," Katherine Bacchus said. "My dad's plants are flying by. The hanging plants are blowing straight out." Mark Bacchus tried to keep the front doors closed by pushing a couch against them, but the wind blew the couches away. "We all hugged each other," Bacchus said. "We stayed in the hall until daylight (Monday)." Flood waters rise There was water in the street up to car hubcaps. "We ate and slept until that afternoon," Katherine Bacchus said. "We were happy. We'd gotten through the storm. But the contractions were really hurting." A break in the 17th Street Canal was flooding the city. The Bacchuses watched looters breaking into houses as the water in the street reached car roof level. "I didn't want my wife and kids in that water," Bacchus said. "It smelled of gasoline." The couple watched rats swim by. By Tuesday afternoon, the Bacchuses were desperate. "Then, this guy in a canoe comes out of nowhere," Bacchus said. "He was in his 50s or 60s. He had, what do you call them, cataracts, and he's bumping into trees. The water was chest high on me. I'm 6-2, and he's a foot shorter, but he didn't care. He wanted to help." The man's 7-year-old daughter was in the canoe with sandwiches and soft drinks. Bacchus and the man pulled the canoe for miles to Memorial Medical only to be turned away by police on the hospital's flooding ramp. It took longer to get back to the house as water in the street rose. The water was halfway up the 15-foot steps to Katherine Bacchus' father's house when they got back. The man with the canoe helped them onto the steps and turned to leave. "I saw him walking away," Bacchus said. "I watched him for three blocks. Then, he made a turn, and I couldn't see him." Second rescue One of Katherine Bacchus' cousins waded up holding a talking bird in a cage over his head, a Beagle in an ice chest and a cell phone. "My contractions were getting harder, and the water kept coming up," Bacchus said. "We're calling 911, but we're getting Jefferson Parish 911, and they're relaying. I'm losing the battery in the cell phone." The Bacchuses got out sheets and flashlights to signal helicopters passing overhead to no avail. About 1 a.m. Wednesday, Katherine Bacchus awoke to brightness she thought was a helicopter's searchlight. "I woke my husband. I said, 'It's a helicopter.' I look out the window, and my cousin's house is on fire." A row of three houses were ablaze. "There was a vacant lot next door to us," Katherine Bacchus said. "I'm open, you know, about to have a baby. I wasn't getting in that water. ? There were cats drowning and dogs howling." A man they'd seen looting earlier cruised by in a bay boat powered by batteries hooked to a trolling motor. The looter took the Bacchuses and their children into the boat, along with some other people. "I'm scared for my life," Katherine Bacchus said, "but we have no choice. We're heading for the projects on Earhart, heading for the Superdome." As the looter hooked onto another boat and people in the water tried to climb in, the boat flipped. "I'm holding onto the side, and my feet aren't touching anything," Katherine Bacchus said. When the boat righted, Bacchus was thrown back on board, landing in the bottom of the boat. "She's up in two seconds," her husband laughed. "Bailing with a bucket." Fire in her eyes Bacchus had grabbed his sons, Mark Jr., 4, and Matthew, 2, and was wading toward the Amtrak station. His wife made it onto the railroad tracks but refused to go further. "I could hear people shooting, and there were people dropping bottles from the Claiborne Street Bridge," she said. Bacchus got his wife to her feet, and they walked to the Superdome. Dehydrated and doubled with labor pains, Katherine was offered a ride in an ambulance on the Dome's outside concourse. "This military guy says I can't take my family," she said. "He saw me cut my eyes." The Bacchuses -- all of them -- rode the ambulance onto the floor of the Dome. At 7 p.m. Wednesday, the family was on the heliport next door. A Blackhawk helicopter crewman said the family couldn't fly together. The pilot looked at Katherine, her husband said, and told the crewman, "Get them onboard." The helicopter took the family to the Louis Armstrong International Airport, and an ambulance drove them to Woman's. The family left New Orleans around 10 p.m. Wednesday. Mason was born nine hours later. Mason has stopped breathing twice, his mother said. He was in her arms in her bed shortly before lunch Friday. His brother, Mark, busied himself with the controls that raise and lower their mother's bed. "I can't sleep," Katherine Bacchus said. "I feel like if I go to sleep I'll be back in that water drowning. ? I can only be happy. I'm not worried about the car or the house. I knew we were going to die." Advocate staff photo by TRAVIS SPRADLING Mark Bacchus, 39, and wife Katherine, 30, of Kenner with sons, newborn Mason, Mark Jr., 4, and Matthew, 2, huddle at Woman's Hospital in Baton Rouge where Mason was born Thursday. Advocate staff photo by TRAVIS SPRADLING Dr. George Rome III gives instructions to Heather Wright, left, and Mary Rose, center, in Woman's Hospital's special care nursery where babies were airlifted from New Orleans Friday. A hospital spokesman said at least one baby born since Sunday was named Katrina. Printer Friendly Version Send this story to a friend Advertisements FEATURES
